##Henan nurses supporting the Han Dynasty: from a "broken" protective clothing to start

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter, Duan Yanchao, intern, Song Wenhui, thepaper.cn

Zhang Yaru also remembers a month ago when he arrived in Wuhan, the team members trained in the hotel for two days to practice wearing off protective clothing.

Although the hospitals have brought some protective materials, but everyone is reluctant to waste protective clothing on the exercise, a suit of protective clothing a pair of gloves, more than 20 doctors took turns to wear off, off to wear..

Finally, the suit was torn, and the gloves were in tatters.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yaru is in the ward. Photo provided by interviewee

Zhang Yaru, a 30-year-old nurse in the Department of gastroenterology at Huai River Hospital of Henan University, one of the first medical teams in Henan to support the Hubei Province, spent 37 days in Wuhan, Hubei Province, from January 27 to March 4 fighting the disease. From the moment I put on my hazmat suit and walked into the isolation ward, from the moment I was nervous enough to hear my heart beating, to the moment my hands shook, to the moment I gradually became firm and brave, from hearing that the critically ill patient "this class will be over in the next class" , no patient died in her ward until recently; from the first full ward to now, almost half of the patients are empty -- as if she is getting better.

The best part of the day, she told The Paper www.thepaper.cn  , was taking over patients who didn't die when they left work. She firmly believed that she would return home with the care of her family. When the time comes, she should comfort her nervous mother and hug her lovely son.

First Time in the room, I could hear my own heartbeat

Recently, after returning from the Fourth Hospital in Wuhan, Zhang and his colleagues sometimes skipped rope skipping and played badminton in the Hotel Plaza, in addition to meeting to discuss patient care plans.

"The units are so powerful in the rear, " Zhang told The Paper, referring to the Henan University sent by the Huai River Hospital for skipping rope and badminton. "everything from groceries and socks to underwear to N95 masks and protective clothing are important supplies, all the units tried their best to raise money and send it to Wuhan. In the early protection of materials are extremely scarce, once a peer expressed envy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yaru (left) exercises with colleagues after work

Rope skipping, playing badminton, is to let the medical staff to enhance exercise, relax. Medical team in the group announced a psychologist's phone, but Zhang Yaru did not call. She said that some "comrades" more serious insomnia, to this end, the medical team with help sleep drugs.

Self-admitted nerve comparison "big strip" , Zhang Yaru feel that his current psychological condition is not bad.

Born and raised in Kaifeng, his parents were businessmen. When she was in college in Shangqiu, she went home every weekend. From school and work to marriage and children, she felt loved and protected and now a mother and a little girl.

On the first day of the first lunar month (January 25) , when the unit notified the application, there is breathing science work experience Zhang Yaru did not hesitate to apply, she according to the request to the leadership sent to her husband agreed to wechat chat screenshots, did not feel afraid, but some excited.

Just before signing up, Zhang Yaru once dreamed that he went to Wuhan to support. Then, as she entered the room, fully clothed in her protective clothing, she felt a sudden and intense sense that the scene was exactly the same as in her dream. She was afraid to tell anyone about the inexplicable.

The Day of registration, Zhang Yaru only told the mother unit to inform the registration. The next day on the high-speed rail, she received a phone call from her mother, mother a cry, she felt bad, can only comfort "all right. ".

Members of the medical team came from various hospitals in Henan Province and spent two days in the hotel training before they were officially admitted to the Fourth Hospital in Wuhan. Although each hospital has some protective materials, but we do not want to waste. Twenty six medical staff at the Henan University took turns using a protective suit to practice.

"In the end, the suit was torn and the gloves were in bad shape, " Zhang said.

The main practice is to take off protective clothing, because from the ward out, protective clothing is contaminated, so to be particularly careful. "every time off, more than one infection risk. " Zhang Yaru calculate off faster, also to more than 30 minutes. Even now, it takes more than 10 minutes.

"When we had the meeting before we went to the hospital, the leader looked quite serious. He thought we were all young and he had to take us back. I felt as if I really faced life and death, " Zhang said.

After the outbreak, the entire inpatient building of Wuhan's Fourth Hospital was converted into a new pneumonia ward. The 26 staff of the Henan University initially worked on the 10th and 11th floors, then added a 12th floor ward, each with about 37 patients.

At that time, Wuhan already had many medical staff to infect. Enter Hind, Zhang Yaru puts on protective clothing for the first time, looking at the oneself in the mirror, feeling some terror. She could hear her heart beating as she pressed the button at the last door.

"I inhale deeply, and I can't stop my hands shaking, " she said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yaru's life photos

Patients praise staff as "good kids, heroes"

Sometimes, Zhang Yaru feels, the exhaustion on the body has reached the limit.

Each shift lasts four hours. To avoid going to the bathroom, you must not eat or drink for two hours before you go to work. At the end of each shift, except below the knees, clothes are often wet. The most difficult is the protective clothing in the situation, such as ear mask earband strangulation pain, body itching, also can not deal with, especially painful. Paramedics also wear diapers in case of an awkward moment.

At first, nearly 40 patients -- nearly 10 of them -- could not take care of themselves, and many needed high-flow oxygen. The patients were able-bodied, couldn't get out of bed or move, and could hear their wheezing clearly. The worst part is the high mortality rate, and it's very fast. "This class still talks to him, next class goes again, the person has no. "

"The initial psychological pressure is really big, every time back to the hotel, will wash for a long time. " Zhang Yaru said, may be because of late hospitalization, patients are very serious, injection feeding water, at any time will cough. Also help some patients change diapers, cleaning up. While emptying the urine of a female patient, she accidentally spilled urine mixed with menstrual blood on her shoe.

After a few days, Zhang Yaru felt, "not so afraid. ".

Because she felt a deep desire to live: the patients were very quiet, and psychological pressure is great. Take Body temperature, if have a fever, immediately can be anxious, say "how can have a fever, I should not have a fever, I can not have a fever" . A lot of patients think they're going down.

In the ward, Zhang and her colleagues find ways to encourage patients. They tell patients about the effects of each drug, try to persuade patients to eat more, and patients to chat closer relationship.

There is an old lady, and Granddaughter Video, Zhang Yaru See, subconscious and little girl fight. The little girl asked if she was an aunt or an uncle, and she said aunt. The girl's mother asked the girl to bow to Zhang Yaru in the video. "I was particularly moved to say thank you for taking care of her grandmother. After hanging up the phone, the Old Lady asked me if I could still see my granddaughter, and I encouraged her to say that I have children too, and we can all see them, " Zhang said.

Whenever a patient dies, health care workers help clean up valuable or meaningful items, such as cellphones, which are sterilized and packed in plastic bags with names and family members notified.

There are many poignant stories. There was an old woman whose daughter, a doctoral adviser, had died in another hospital during the course of her treatment. One night, an elderly man admitted his son, who was in his 40s and suffering from epilepsy, to the hospital. His mind was like a child's. The old man was worried and wanted to stay here, but his condition was only suitable for going to the shelter hospital. The old man's wife and father died of new pneumonia. When he left, he made sure to give his son his medicine on time. We told him he had to hold on because he had a son to look after.

"It was really sad. My colleagues were all in tears, " Zhang said.

In the ward, there are many warm moments. 26 bed GRANDPA, every time Zhang Yaru to give him infusion, will thumbs up, praise they are good children, but also a hero. Zhang Yaru will also encourage the old GRANDPA, "with us, you will be better! "

One day, she felt the most heartwarming thing, is the old man had an extra bowl of porridge, "he did not know, he asked me for an extra bowl of porridge, my heart is how excited. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sunset in Wuhan, February 17,2010, photographed by Zhang Yaru

"Come on, it must be tough. "

Zhang Yaru is the most happy thing every day, is the handover of the book at the end of the day did not disappear due to death of patients.

She told The Paper that things were getting better and better in the ten days or so that the shelter was open.

At present, Zhang Yaru in the ward, only 20 patients, the empty bed rate of nearly 50 percent. Health care workers who have not taken a break for several days can take one day off each week. The most gratifying thing is that more and more patients are cured and fewer and fewer people die. She's in a ward where no one has died in two weeks.

On February 27, two patients were discharged from Zhang's ward. One is an 80-year-old grandmother, the other is a university teacher. They thanked the paramedics for saving their lives. Help them carry luggage, send them out of the hospital, no hug, no handshake, looking at the two smiling eyes, Zhang Yaru think, all pay is worth it.

She told The Paper that because they arrived early, their hotel was in good condition, and although they were not used to the food, there was not much demand for it. "Come, affirmation is to eat bitter, want to eat popular drink spicy be impossible. " She said with a smile.

It's just that the N95 mask is a little tight right now, and she only has five left. The 8 a.m. to 12 a.m. class was the one with the most frequent contact with the patient, and she was reluctant to use it until she met the class.

In 2003, when Zhang Yaru was in junior high school, the biggest impression was that she was not allowed to attend classes. No one would have thought, she would now as a nurse, into such a "war epidemic. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yaru's diary

In her diary, Zhang Yaru wrote that she was relieved that her son had been taken care of by his family, "because I am a clumsy mother, will only take him to play games, doing is always dark cooking. But, Mother's little prince, now, your mother is doing a particularly powerful thing. ".

Every day, my mother would video-chat with Zhang Yaru at least once. If we don't, mother won't be able to sleep. She and her mother usually talk about everything, at least 40 minutes at a time.

On the phone, her sweet son would ask her why she hadn't gone back. She always told her son, "wait till mom beats the virus. The son did not know that this is about life and death, will be happy to clap said, "go mom. ". She can't let her son get scared, send him pictures of herself, and tell him she can't go out yet because she hasn't won yet.

In eight days, it is my son's fourth birthday, and Zhang Yaru can not go back in time. She said, when the victory to return, to the mother to make up a reunion year, to make up a birthday for his son. All she wanted to do was comfort her nervous mother, hug her little prince, and eat something nice.

A few days ago, Zhang Yaru once photographed the setting sun in Wuhan. The tall buildings were gray and gloomy in the dusk, and the sky was a beautiful, shining sunset.

This issue is edited by Yu Hua Zhou
